</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" pageId="20" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[685,1173,1017,1729]" pageId="20">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,880,1496,1517]" pageId="20">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity box="[960,1032,1496,1517]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="20" unit="mm" value="4.8">4.8 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[1097,1169,1496,1517]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="20" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,741,1522,1543]" pageId="20">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation box="[817,900,1522,1543]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="24.[175,215,1483,1502]" captionTargetBox="[153,1171,193,1460]" captionTargetId="figure-62@24.[151,1172,192,1460]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="Figs. 110–115. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 110) P. catarina; 111) P. macilentus; 112) P. megalus; 113) P. argus;" pageId="20">Fig. 114</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[911,1027,1522,1543]" pageId="20">Integument</emphasis>
: Head, thorax, and mesoscutellum yellow; antenna brown; elytra black; legs mostly brown, femoral base yellow; pterothorax, and abdomen black. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1011,1064,1602,1623]" pageId="20">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes narrower than vertex (12:15); funicular antennomeres slightly expanded, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[882,896,1650,1664]" fontSize="6" pageId="20">th</superScript>
antennomere not acuminate (
<figureCitation box="[692,769,1682,1703]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="17.[197,238,885,904]" captionTargetBox="[189,1161,210,871]" captionTargetId="figure-364@17.[172,1193,183,875]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs. 39–47. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 39) P. macilentus; 40) P. megalus; 41) P. argus; 42) P. aspigalbus;" pageId="20">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[791,866,1682,1703]" pageId="20">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum transverse (35:30), lateral tubercle moderately prominent (
<figureCitation box="[1082,1160,1708,1729]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="19.[197,237,1538,1557]" captionTargetBox="[190,1193,191,1524]" captionTargetId="figure-1@19.[172,1193,183,1534]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs. 62–75. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 62) P. oxinus; 63) P. alajuela; 64) P. megacavus; 65) P. alboordinus; 66) P. pallidus; 67) P. apolegmus; 68) P. catarina; 69) P. macilentus; 70) P. megalus; 71) P. argus; 72) P. aspigalbus; 73) P. flora; 74) P. posticalis; 75) P. ostrinus." pageId="20">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
);
</paragraph>
